{#- VARIANT DETAIL (definition) — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="qbo-feat-projects-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">What QuickBooks Online Projects is, plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Projects is the job-costing feature in QuickBooks Online. A project is a container for one job, engagement, or contract &mdash; tied to a customer &mdash; that gathers everything financial about that job in a single place. Instead of seeing only company-wide income and expenses, you see income, costs, labor, and profit for each project on its own. The feature is available in QuickBooks Online <em>Plus</em> and <em>Advanced</em>; the lower plans don&rsquo;t include it.</p>
      <p>The way it works is by <em>assignment</em>. After you turn Projects on and create a project, you tag the transactions that belong to it: the invoices you bill the customer, the expenses and bills you incur on the job, the estimates you quote, and the billable time your team logs against it. QuickBooks then rolls all of that up into the project&rsquo;s income, its costs, and a running profitability figure &mdash; so a job that looked busy but barely cleared its costs shows up as exactly that, while a quietly profitable one is visible too.</p>
      <p>It&rsquo;s worth being precise about what makes it accurate. Projects doesn&rsquo;t infer anything &mdash; it only reports on what you assign to it. A project is only as true as the transactions tagged to it; an expense left unassigned, or income posted to the customer but not the project, simply won&rsquo;t appear in that job&rsquo;s profitability. We describe QuickBooks Online&rsquo;s behavior as it actually works &mdash; we don&rsquo;t claim capabilities the feature doesn&rsquo;t have.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

